 ---

 ## The Problem

 You can usually tell **that** an agent run went wrong. It is much harder to explain **why**, decide **what to change next**, and verify whether the change actually helped.

 A folder fills up with JSONL sessions. Somewhere inside are tool failures, weak prompts, token spikes, flaky searches, and the occasional run that really did get better. But raw logs alone do not tell you which bottleneck matters, what to optimize first, or whether the extra spend was worth it.

 So the real questions start stacking up: **Where is the bottleneck? Which prompt or model choice is hurting performance? What should I optimize next? Did the latest change improve the agent, or just move the cost around?**

 That is where ClawClip comes in. It turns local agent runs into replayable evidence, diagnosable bottlenecks, optimization directions, and measurable progress — in minutes instead of midnight.

 ---

 ## Features

 | | Feature | What it gives you |
 | --- | --- | --- |
-| 🎬 | **Run Replay** | Reconstruct each run as step-by-step evidence so you can see where failures, retries, and wasted effort actually happened |
+| 🎬 | **Run Diagnostics** | Reconstruct each run as step-by-step evidence so you can see where failures, retries, and wasted effort actually happened |
 | 📊 | **Agent Scorecards** | Score core capabilities, surface weak dimensions, and prove whether optimization work is making the agent stronger |
 | 💸 | **Cost Analysis** | Break down spend by model, task, and trend so you can spot waste and optimize routing decisions |
 | ☁️ | **Word Cloud & Tags** | Auto-extract keywords, categories, and session labels to quickly understand what your agents have been doing |
 | 🏆 | **Progress Comparison** | Compare agents or runs side by side to see which setup is improving and which one is regressing |
 | 🪄 | **Optimization Suggestions** | Turn usage and spend patterns into concrete next-step ideas for prompts, models, and workflow strategy |
 | 📚 | **Knowledge Base** | Import session JSON, search historical runs, and build a local memory layer for debugging and iteration |
 | 🧩 | **Template Market** | Reuse proven agent scenarios and working setups instead of starting every experiment from scratch |

 ---

 ## Why ClawClip

 ### Diagnose before you optimize
 Replay is only the entry point. ClawClip helps you see which capability is weak, where the bottleneck sits, and what to change next.

 ### Prove progress, not vibes
 Scorecards, comparisons, and trend views help you verify whether a prompt, model, or workflow change actually improved the agent.

 ### Keep optimization local and cheap
 Benchmarks and analysis run offline. No LLM API calls. No surprise bill just to understand yesterday's run.

 ### Framework agnostic
 Built for OpenClaw, works with ZeroClaw, and fits any agent workflow that writes JSONL sessions.

 ---

 ## Data Sources

 | Source | Notes |
 | --- | --- |
 | `~/.openclaw/` | Auto-detected on startup |
 | `OPENCLAW_STATE_DIR` | Override the default session directory |
 | `CLAWCLIP_LOBSTER_DIRS` | Add extra folders for scanning |
 | Built-in demo sessions | Explore the product immediately, even with no real data |
 | SQLite-only setups | ClawClip currently focuses on the official JSONL session path |

 ---

 ## Tech Stack

 Express + TypeScript · React 18 · Vite · Tailwind CSS · Recharts · Framer Motion · Lucide React

